            <div type="translation">
                <p>Μήτηρ Θεοῦ. ἡ Μαχαιρωθεῖσα. / Θεοτόκε βοήθει τῷ σῷ δούλῳ Πέτρῳ διακόνῳ καὶ χαρτοφύλακι.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Mother of god. <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi>. / Mother of God help your servant Petros, deacon and <hi rend="italic">chartophylax</hi>.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">Muttergottes. <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi>. / Gottesgebährerin, hilf deinem Diener Petros, dem Diakon und <hi rend="italic">chartophylax</hi>.</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p>According to W. Seibt, the iconographical type of the Mother of God <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi>, i.e. “stabbed with a knife”, corresponds to a standing Mother of God holding the medallion with Christ in her hands before her chest, thus closely related to the type of the Virgin <hi rend="italic">Nikopoios</hi>, the victory-maker.[1] The epithet μαχαιρωθεῖσα, classified by G. P. Galavaris among the so-called “popular” epithets describing a particular iconography of the Virgin, might refer to a miracle that happened in the Hagia Sophia in Constantinople. According to the account of Anthony, Archbishop of Novgorod (who, on his visit to Constantinople in 1200, allegedly saw a stabbed icon of the Mother of God in the Hagia Sophia), a Jew once stabbed the Christ child held by the Virgin on that very icon with a knife, and blood poured out of it.[2]</p>
                <p>The owner of this seal, Petros,[3] is known both from documentary sources and from another seal he left, which bears the same, peculiar iconography of the Mother of God <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi>.[4] He participated as deacon and <hi rend="italic">chartophylax</hi> in the synod of the Blachernai at the end of 1094[5] and signed a synodal document as archdeacon and <hi rend="italic">chartophylax</hi> in 1101.[6]</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="footnotes">
                  <p xml:id="footnote-1">
                      [1]. See <bibl><ptr target="Seibt1987"/>, <citedRange unit="page">here p. 45 and n. 28 with earlier bibliography</citedRange></bibl>. On the epithets relating to the Mother of God, see also <bibl><ptr target="Hunger1994"/>, for a discussion on the <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi>, see <citedRange unit="page">p. 132</citedRange></bibl>. 
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-2">
                      [2]. See <bibl><ptr target="Galavaris1959"/>, <citedRange unit="page">here p. 231</citedRange></bibl> with more accounts and testimonies relating to the miracle of the stabbed icon.</p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-3">
                      [3]. <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/person/Petros/105/">Petros no. 105</ref></citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"> <ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/boulloterion/1430/">Boulloterion no. 1430</ref></citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                <p xml:id="footnote-4">
                    [4]. <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"> <ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/boulloterion/1429/">Boulloterion no. 1429</ref></citedRange></bibl>. The seal bears on the obverse the image of the Mother of God <hi rend="italic">Machairotheisa</hi> and on the reverse a metrical inscription reading: Πέτρον, Πάναγνε, χαρτοφύλακαν (<hi rend="italic">sic!</hi>) σκέποις. There is no doubt as to the identification of the owner of the seal. Three specimina issuing from the same boulloterion are known so far: Geneva, CdN 2004-309, Dumbarton Oaks BZS.1955.1.4995, and State Hermitage Museum M-414.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="footnote-5">
                    [5]. See <bibl><ptr target="Gautier1971"/>, <citedRange unit="page">p. 219</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                <p xml:id="footnote-6">
                    [6]. See <bibl><ptr target="Gautier1969"/>, <citedRange unit="page">here p. 160-161</citedRange></bibl>. See also the commentary to seal no. 261 published in <bibl><ptr target="ZacosGenève"/></bibl>, with earlier bibliography.
                </p>
              </div>
